{
  "analysis": "POLICY 0.1: For an evergreen reference page about a cruise ship (not a specific sailing/itinerary, not a booking/offer page), the primary entity is the ship itself, which is a physical vehicle, plus the page content, which is a reference/guide. Schema.org defines Vehicle as “a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space” and explicitly models Vehicle as a subtype of Product. [[1, 2]] That makes Vehicle a more semantically precise choice than bare Product while still inheriting all Product properties when needed. TouristAttraction is intended as an additionalType that can be layered onto many different base types (including non-Place types) when something functions as a tourist draw. [[3]] [[4]] Travel SEO specialists consistently recommend using the most specific correct type but also warn against proliferating complex schema that doesn’t map to real user-visible content or Google rich-result support; they also emphasize that TouristAttraction is most suitable when a thing is treated as a destination or attraction in its own right. [[5]] [[6]] [[7]] [[8]] [[9]] For cruise itineraries themselves, discussion on Moz and Webmasters StackExchange notes there is no perfect schema; Event or Trip/TouristTrip may be appropriate for specific dated sailings, whereas Product can describe bookable packages, but experts stress that you should choose types that match actual content and supported rich results rather than forcing a type just to ‘have’ schema. [[10]] [[11]] [[12]] Given cruisinginthewake.com is an independent reference/logbook site that doesn’t sell cruises or host booking offers [[13]], modeling each ship page as a Product without offers attached is semantically weaker than modeling the ship as Vehicle, optionally with additionalType TouristAttraction when the ship is framed as an attraction/destination. The page itself can remain typed as WebPage/FAQPage (already present) and optionally Article/CreativeWork for the narrative content.\n\nPOLICY 0.4: The 89 JSON page data files represent an unused, partially complete data layer for ship-specific details (trackers, deck plans, dining, statistics, related ships). The current site already exposes key content directly in static HTML, aligning with technical SEO guidance that search-critical content should be rendered to HTML via SSR/SSG rather than only via client-side JavaScript. [[14]] Modern SEO references emphasise that broken or half-implemented schema and data layers are common and frequently ignored or counterproductive, and that a small number of accurate, validated schema blocks is better than many incomplete implementations. [[9]] Retaining an unused JSON layer creates divergence risks between HTML and JSON, encourages ‘compliance theatre’, and can lead to key facts only being updated in one representation. On the other hand, if the project commits to using these JSON files as a canonical, validated source to hydrate purely presentational enhancements (e.g., tracker embeds, preview images) while still ensuring all critical facts remain in HTML, then a loader can be an asset rather than a liability. Any solution must respect the requirement that key content be present in static HTML—JavaScript can enhance but must not be the only source for facts that schema or crawlers rely on. [[14]] The extra ‘dining / stateroom / itinerary / reviews’ research request in the prompt doesn’t specify a particular ship or line, so it cannot be meaningfully or accurately fulfilled as written without guessing; I therefore exclude it from factual claims.",
  "claims": [
    {
      "type": "schema_definition",
      "claim": "Schema.org defines Vehicle as “a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space,” and Vehicle is a subtype of Product.",
      "source": "Schema.org Vehicle and automotive documentation",
      "url": "https://schema.org/Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_definition",
      "claim": "Schema.org’s automotive documentation notes that Vehicle is a subtype of Product and is intended as the top type for describing vehicles such as cars, buses, and related transport objects.",
      "source": "Schema.org automotive extension docs",
      "url": "https://schema.org/docs/automotive.html"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_definition",
      "claim": "Product in Schema.org is defined broadly as any offered product or service, including tangible items, services, tickets, rentals, or streamed content, not only physical goods.",
      "source": "Schema.org Product type definition",
      "url": "https://schema.org/Product"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_definition",
      "claim": "TouristAttraction is a subtype of Place that can be added as an extra type (additionalType) to other entities when something functions as a tourist attraction, according to tourism-focused Schema.org guidance.",
      "source": "Data Liberate’s tourism schema explanation of TouristAttraction",
      "url": "https://dataliberate.com/2017/09/19/schema-org-for-tourism/"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_usage_guidance",
      "claim": "Tourism schema practitioners recommend using TouristAttraction schema when an entity is treated as a specific attraction or venue, and suggest that it can be layered on top of another base type rather than used alone.",
      "source": "TouristAttraction schema generator and guide; tourism schema articles",
      "url": "https://schemantra.com/schema_list/TouristAttraction"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_usage_guidance",
      "claim": "Travel SEO specialists recommend using the most specific applicable Schema.org types such as TouristAttraction or LocalBusiness instead of generic Place, but also stress focusing on types that map to real content and supported rich results.",
      "source": "Travel SEO schema strategy articles",
      "url": "https://blackbearmedia.io/11-powerful-schema-markup-strategies-for-travel-websites/"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_usage_guidance",
      "claim": "Another travel SEO guide for 2026 lists LodgingBusiness, TouristAttraction, Offer, and Review as key schemas and recommends nested schemas but only where they fit actual travel content.",
      "source": "Schema markup for travel SEO article",
      "url": "https://618media.com/en/blog/schema-markup-for-travel-seo/"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_discussion",
      "claim": "Moz community discussion on cruise markup concludes there is no perfect schema type for cruises, with practitioners debating Event vs Product and noting that Trip would be ideal but is not yet widely supported for rich results.",
      "source": "Moz Q&A on marking up cruises as events or products",
      "url": "https://moz.com/community/q/topic/68489/could-i-set-a-cruise-as-an-event-in-schema-mark-up"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_discussion",
      "claim": "A Webmasters StackExchange thread on cruise schema notes that for specific dated cruises, Event may be appropriate if properties like startDate and endDate are present, while generic trip packages without fixed dates resemble Products.",
      "source": "Webmasters StackExchange discussion on what Schema.org type to use for a cruise",
      "url": "https://webmasters.stackexchange.com/questions/123035/what-schema-org-type-should-you-use-for-a-cruise"
    },
    {
      "type": "site_profile",
      "claim": "Cruisinginthewake.com describes itself as an independent cruise traveler’s logbook that offers planning tools, ship comparison, menus, cabin scouting, and accessibility notes, explicitly stating that it does not sell cruises or earn commissions.",
      "source": "Cruising In the Wake homepage description",
      "url": "https://cruisinginthewake.com/"
    },
    {
      "type": "seo_best_practice",
      "claim": "Technical SEO guidance for modern CMS/frontends stresses that pre-rendered or server-rendered HTML (SSR/SSG) is a “non-negotiable” baseline so content is directly available to crawlers; structured data should be consistent with visible content and not rely solely on client-side JavaScript.",
      "source": "Strapi/technical SEO guide discussing SSR/SSG and structured data",
      "url": "https://strapi.io/blog/how-to-improve-technical-seo"
    },
    {
      "type": "schema_quality_guidance",
      "claim": "A 2026 structured data reference recommends shipping a small number of accurate, validated schema blocks, warning that broken or misapplied schema is common and may be ignored or trigger problems.",
      "source": "Complete schema markup reference guide",
      "url": "https://www.digitalapplied.com/blog/schema-markup-types-complete-structured-data-reference"
    }
  ],
  "proposed_update": {
    "POLICY_0_1": {
      "verdict": "Product alone is not the strongest type; prefer Vehicle as the primary entity for the ship, optionally with additionalType TouristAttraction where the ship is positioned as a destination or attraction. Keep WebPage/FAQPage for the page itself and, if desired, add Article/CreativeWork for long-form reference content.",
      "recommended_schema_pattern": {
        "page_entity": [
          "@type": "WebPage",
          "additionalType": ["FAQPage", "Article" (optional)]
        ],
        "ship_entity": [
          "@type": "Vehicle",
          "additionalType": ["TouristAttraction" (only when the ship itself is framed as an attraction)],
          "mainEntityOfPage": "URL of the ship page"
        ]
      },
      "touristattraction_node": "Use TouristAttraction as an additionalType on the Vehicle node instead of a separate sibling node, and only when the content actually treats the ship as an attraction in its own right. For most reference-only ship pages, TouristAttraction is optional and may be omitted to avoid over-engineering."
    },
    "POLICY_0_4": {
      "verdict": "The JSON page data layer is acceptable to keep only if you fully commit to using it for non-critical UI enhancements and keep HTML as the canonical source of key facts. Otherwise, the safest path is to remove or archive it to avoid divergence and schema-gaming incentives.",
      "recommended_approach": "Either: (A) Promote the JSON files to a maintained, validated data layer used by a small, documented JS loader that hydrates non-critical widgets (tracker embeds, deck-plan previews, sister-ship links) while ensuring all key facts remain in the static HTML; or (B) Deprecate and delete/externally archive the unused JSON files before migration to reduce technical debt and avoid incentivizing hidden or inconsistent data. In both cases, enforce that schema.org markup only references facts visible in the HTML."
    }
  },
  "risks": [
    "If the site models an evergreen ship reference page purely as Product without clear offers, search engines may treat the markup as weak or inconsistent with expectations for product-rich results, reducing any practical benefit.",
    "Introducing a separate TouristAttraction sibling node for each ship, without strong on-page emphasis that the ship is an attraction and without clear rich-result support, adds maintenance complexity and increases the risk of validation issues without clear SEO upside.",
    "Keeping the 89 JSON page files but only partially using them increases the chance that HTML and JSON disagree (e.g., restaurant names, stats, registry), undermining data trust for users and search engines and potentially causing structured data to reference stale or invisible facts.",
    "Building a JS loader that populates critical information (ship stats, dining lists) exclusively from JSON at runtime would violate the requirement that key content be present in static HTML and could result in crawlers missing important content if JavaScript fails or is delayed.",
    "Deleting the JSON files without a clear migration plan discards a potentially useful future data layer for tools such as the Ship Size Atlas or internal consistency checks; this may force re-scraping or manual re-entry later if a centralized ship data model is desired.",
    "Overly complex schema graphs (Vehicle + TouristAttraction + multiple nested nodes) across 290 ship pages increase the chance of implementation bugs and manual actions, particularly if some properties are left empty or out of sync during the migration."
  ],
  "confidence": 0.74,
  "verdicts": [
    {
      "PROPOSAL_ID": "claude_1",
      "VERDICT": "WHEAT_WITH_REFINEMENT",
      "JUSTIFICATION": "The core instinct to move away from using Cruise (an itinerary-style/trip entity) or Thing for evergreen ship reference pages is sound; these types are misaligned with a static ship profile. Using a commercially oriented type like Product does align with Schema.org’s pattern of modeling vehicles as Product subclasses (via Vehicle) [[1]] [[2]], and Claude’s mention of an optional TouristAttraction node recognizes that some ships function as attractions. However, Product as the primary type for the ship is less specific than Vehicle, and many travel-SEO sources stress using the most precise applicable type while avoiding needless complexity. [[5]] [[6]] [[7]] TouristAttraction is better attached as an additionalType to the ship entity only where the content clearly frames the ship as a destination or attraction, rather than being mandated or always modeled as a separate sibling node. [[3]] [[4]] The proposal also doesn’t address the benefit of keeping the page itself typed as WebPage/FAQPage/Article and linking to the ship entity via mainEntity or mainEntityOfPage. On POLICY 0.4, Claude is right to be wary of deleting potentially useful JSON and right to consider a JS loader with HTML fallback, but the proposal underplays the risks of drift between HTML and JSON and the modern SEO guidance that emphasizes pre-rendered HTML and a small number of accurate, validated schemas over half-implemented data layers. [[14]] [[9]] Overall, the direction is correct but needs tightening around choosing Vehicle over bare Product, limiting TouristAttraction to real-attraction cases, and deciding either to fully adopt or fully retire the JSON data layer.",
      "REFINEMENT": {
        "POLICY_0_1": [
          "Use Vehicle as the primary @type for the ship entity; it is a subtype of Product and semantically correct for a cruise ship, while still allowing access to Product properties as needed. [[1]] [[2]]",
          "Keep the page-level entity as WebPage (and FAQPage/Article where appropriate) and link to the ship entity via mainEntity or mainEntityOfPage, rather than conflating the page and the ship into a single Product node.",
          "Apply TouristAttraction only when the ship is clearly positioned as a tourist draw or destination; attach it as an additionalType on the Vehicle node instead of introducing a separate sibling JSON-LD node, to avoid schema sprawl while still signaling its attraction role where relevant. [[3]] [[4]]",
          "Do not chase unsupported types purely for semantics (e.g., Trip/TouristTrip) on these evergreen reference pages, since community discussion indicates limited rich-result benefits and advises choosing types that map to supported features and actual page content. [[10]] [[11]]"
        ],
        "POLICY_0_4": [
          "Before building a JS loader, define a contract that all key ship facts (stats, registry, primary dining list, core amenities) must originate in and remain visible in static HTML, in line with technical SEO guidance that crawlers should see complete content without executing JavaScript. [[14]]",
          "If the JSON files are retained, treat them as a maintained data layer: add tests or build-time validation against schema (e.g., checking that JSON values match visible HTML tables and that no stale fields remain). Otherwise, decommission them explicitly (e.g., move out of the public assets pipeline or into an archival repo) to remove the incentive for validator-only ‘compliance theatre’. [[9]]",
          "Limit JSON-driven enhancements to non-critical, obviously decorative or convenience features (e.g., tracker embed configuration, deck-plan preview image URLs, sister-ship cross-links) so that any JS failure does not affect the completeness of content or schema.",
          "As part of the 290-ship migration, standardize a single pattern either with or without this JSON layer; mixed strategies (some ships using the loader, others not) will be harder to reason about and test at scale."
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "proposals": [
    {
      "PROPOSAL": "Model each ship as a Vehicle entity with optional additionalType TouristAttraction, and keep the existing WebPage/FAQPage structure as the page-level entity linked via mainEntityOfPage, rather than making Product the primary mainEntity.",
      "CONFIDENCE": "HIGH",
      "JUSTIFICATION": "Schema.org explicitly defines Vehicle as the type for objects that transport people or cargo and places Vehicle as a subtype of Product, making it a precise semantic fit for cruise ships. [[1]] [[2]] This retains all Product capabilities while providing clearer meaning to search engines and aligns with tourism schema guidance encouraging the most specific applicable type. [[5]] [[6]] TouristAttraction can then be layered on only for ships presented as attractions by using it as an additionalType on the Vehicle node, consistent with tourism community recommendations. [[3]] [[4]]"
    },
    {
      "PROPOSAL": "Use TouristAttraction sparingly and as additionalType rather than a separate sibling node, focusing on hero or highly marketed ships where the ‘floating resort’ or ‘destination itself’ narrative is strong.",
      "CONFIDENCE": "MEDIUM",
      "JUSTIFICATION": "Travel SEO case studies show TouristAttraction schema helping when applied to true attractions or destinations, but not every location-like thing needs that label. [[6]] [[7]] The tourism community notes that virtually any entity can be a TouristAttraction, but the intent is to mark things that function as attractions for tourists. [[3]] Using TouristAttraction as an additionalType on a subset of ships whose content emphasizes them as destinations balances semantic expressiveness against implementation complexity."
    },
    {
      "PROPOSAL": "Either formalize the page.json files into a canonical ship data layer with validation and limited JS hydration for non-critical UI, or archive/delete them entirely; avoid a middle ground where they remain unused but present.",
      "CONFIDENCE": "HIGH",
      "JUSTIFICATION": "Technical SEO sources emphasize that static HTML (via SSR/SSG) should contain the authoritative content and that structured data must be consistent with what users see, not driven by hidden or stale data stores. [[14]] [[9]] Retaining a dormant JSON layer invites data drift and ‘compliance theatre’ behavior, particularly when it was previously used to game validators. Conversely, if the JSON files are promoted to a maintained data layer and used strictly for non-critical enhancements (trackers, deck-plan thumbnails, cross-linking), they can add value without violating the requirement that key content be static and visible."
    },
    {
      "PROPOSAL": "Introduce automated checks in the build or deployment pipeline to ensure that structured data never references information absent from the visible HTML (e.g., dining venues or stats only present in JSON), especially if the JSON loader path is adopted.",
      "CONFIDENCE": "MEDIUM",
      "JUSTIFICATION": "Guidance on schema implementation warns that hidden or mismatched schema—where JSON-LD claims facts not present on the page—is treated as spammy and can be ignored or penalized. [[9]] [[14]] With 290 ship pages, manual policing is unrealistic; adding automated checks (e.g., verifying that key properties like name, gt, guests, registry appear both in HTML and in any linked data layer) reduces the risk of accidental divergence and protects against future regressions."
    },
    {
      "PROPOSAL": "Keep the existing JSON-LD stack (Organization/WebSite/BreadcrumbList/Review/Person/WebPage/FAQPage) minimal and accurate, and resist adding Exotic tourism types (TouristTrip, TouristDestination) to ship pages until there is a clear feature or rich-result target.",
      "CONFIDENCE": "MEDIUM",
      "JUSTIFICATION": "Webmasters StackExchange and Moz discussions on travel schema note that some tourism-oriented types like Trip/TouristTrip exist but are not widely surfaced in rich results, and that shoehorning pages into unsupported types yields little benefit while increasing maintenance burden. [[10]] [[11]] [[12]] A 2026 schema reference guide similarly recommends prioritizing a small number of accurate, validated schemas aligned with actual search features rather than broad coverage for its own sake. [[9]]"
    }
  ],
  "low_hanging_fruit": [
    {
      "item": "Switch from using generic Product to the more specific Vehicle type for ship entities while keeping the rest of the schema graph largely unchanged.",
      "justification": "Vehicle is an immediate subtype of Product specifically designed for transport devices, so changing @type from Product to Vehicle gains semantic precision with minimal template changes. [[1]] [[2]] This is a template-level adjustment that can be rolled out across all migrated ships with low risk."
    },
    {
      "item": "Attach TouristAttraction as additionalType on only a small curated set of high-profile ships and evaluate impact before scaling.",
      "justification": "TouristAttraction is most beneficial where entities are clearly attractions; starting with a handful of ships heavily marketed as destinations enables monitoring of structured-data validation and any SERP changes before incurring the overhead of fleet-wide implementation. [[3]] [[6]]"
    },
    {
      "item": "Run all existing and revised JSON-LD through both Schema.org’s validator and Google’s Rich Results Test as part of the migration process.",
      "justification": "Travel and general schema references highlight that many implementations fail due to simple validation errors and recommend always validating before shipping. [[7]] [[9]] Adding validation to your migration pipeline is a straightforward, high-value safeguard."
    },
    {
      "item": "If page.json is retained, immediately strip or refactor any fields that are not currently surfaced in HTML to prevent accidental reintroduction of ‘hidden’ facts later.",
      "justification": "Given the history of validator gaming, any fields that exist only in JSON but not on the page are liabilities. Removing or clearly segregating them now reduces future temptation and simplifies compliance with the requirement that key facts remain in static HTML. [[14]] [[9]]"
    }
  ]
}

